flowRoot.flowPara: Not that great: gives a lot of space to month and year even though these are less common. You can only see a week ahead.
Days of the week would update when you change the month/year.
Better use of space, but doesn't give you much more.
Mixes vertical and horizontal movement - not so cool.
Updated version of the existing GTK+ date picker.
Pretty good in a number of respects:
Efficiently flows from the top to bottom - choose the month if you need to, then the day.
Consistent use of horizontal navigation.
Consistent with the main calendar UI.
Could easily indicate date ranges
Central row is always selected - scrolling changes the selection. Clicking a row moves the list and selects it.
Date Selection
Time Selection
Simple helper picker. Only allows picking for half hour increments (this is similar to how the web version of Google Calendar works).
Has the advantage of being simple and straightforward. The picker itself would work well for touch, but you would have to use an on screen keyboard to enter an exact time.
More efficient than the version above.
Simple helper pickers. Only allows picking for 5 minute increments.
Buttons allow tweaking the time per minute.
Should be efficient, particularly with a pointer. Recognition might be an issue - it doesn't look like the time.
Time updates with the selection below. It can be tweaked with the +/- buttons.
Showing every minute could create a lot of scrolling here.
Could be a bit painful if you have to use the scroll bars?
Middle row is always selected - scrolling changes the selection. Clicking a row selects it, moving the column in the process.
Nice and simple!
AM/PM version.
Could indicate a range?
I really like the way this focusses on 5 minute increments. The manual adjustment part is the weakest part.
You could leave the tweaking part to the text entry, I suppose...
